{"title_page": "Sadhana Shivdasani", "text_new": "{{other uses2|Sadhana}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sadhana Shivdasani\n| image              = Nanda Waheeda Helen Sadhana.jpg\n| caption            = Sadhana (furthest right) alongside Nanda (left), Waheeda Rehman and Helen (middle)\n| birth_name         = Sadhana Shivdasani\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1941|09|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Karachi]], [[Sind Province (1936\u201355)|Sind]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2015|12|25|1941|09|02|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| resting_place      = [[Oshiwara]], Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| residence          = [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], Mumbai, Mahrashtra, India\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Jai Hind College]], Mumbai\n| occupation         = * [[Actress]]\n* [[film producer]]\n* [[film director]]\n| other_names        = Sadhana<br>''The Mystery Girl''\n| known_for          = [[Bollywood]] films and songs\n| style              = Sadhana cut\n| spouse             = {{marriage|R.K. Nayyar|1966|1995|end=died}}\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Shivdasani family|Shivdasani family]]\n| awards             = [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award]] (2002)\n| years_active       = 1958\u20131978\n}}\n\n'''Sadhana Shivdasani''' (2 September 1941 \u2013 25 December 2015), popularly known by the mononym '''Sadhana''', was an Indian film actress, who appeared in many successful films of 1960s and 70s. Regarded as one of the finest and iconic film actresses in the history of [[Hindi cinema]], Sadhana was the highest-paid actress of her time from early 1960s to late 1970s. Popularly known as ''The Mystery Girl'', Sadhana was one of the most beautiful and the top actresses in the 1960s, a period regarded as [[Bollywood]]'s \"golden era\". She was active from 1960-1981.<ref name=hindu>{{cite news|title=Bollywood, kin, bid adieu to Sadhana|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/news/bollywood-kin-bid-adieu-to-sadhana/article8033705.ece|work=The Hindu|date=27 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadhana Shivdasani Cremated, Waheeda Rehman, Asha Parekh Bid Farewell|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/sadhana-shivdasani-cremated-waheeda-rehman-asha-parekh-bid-farewell-1259238|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Sadhana starred in over 30 successful films such as ''Hum Dono'', ''Woh Kaun Thi'', Rajkumar, Waqt, Mere Mehboob, Mera Saaya, Anita, Sachaai and Ek Phool do mali. Shivdasani appeared in the [[Sindhi language]] film ''Abaana'' and entered the [[Bollywood|Hindi film industry]] through the 1960s romantic film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. Her [[fringe (hair)|fringe haircut]] became popular during the 1960s and came to be known as the \"Sadhana cut\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadhana: The actor with the timeless elegance, the fringe and that outfit|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/in-the-60s-there-was-nothing-as-influential-as-the-sadhana-cut|newspaper=The Indian Express|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadhana will always be remembered for her trendsetting 'Sadhana cut' hairstyle, say fans|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/lifestyle-2/sadhana-will-always-be-remembered-as-a-trendsetter-say-fans-1181792.html|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe became famous with her three suspense thriller films; ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' (1964), ''[[Mera Saaya]]'' (1966) and ''[[Anita (1967 film)|Anita]]'' (1967), all directed by [[Raj Khosla]]. Sadhana was given a double role in her two commercial successful films ''Woh Kaun Thi?'' and ''Mera Saaya''. She was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress]] for films such as ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' and ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]]'' in 1965 and 1966 respectively. She took retirement from the film industry in the mid-1970s before which she also directed and co-produced a few films. She received the [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award]] for her contributions to hit and evergreen classic films of [[Bollywood]].\n\nSadhana married her ''Love in Shimla'' director R.K. Nayyar in 1966. Their marriage lasted for 30 years and ended when R.K. Nayyar died in 1995. Sadhana never married after his death and lived alone for most of her life. Sadhana was diagnosed with [[cancer]] in her old age that led her to her death on 25 December 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nSadhana was born Sadhana Shivdasani in a [[Sindhi Hindus|Sindhi Hindu]] family<ref name=Interview1991>{{cite magazine|url=https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=13wK4lve5tli4rLyLAGXDjBkgiHD7MPh9kaw63qlRJmc|title=The Sadhana Mystique|magazine=Filmfare|date=July 1991|author=Punita Bhatt|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> in [[Karachi]], [[British Raj|British India]] on 2 September 1941. She was an only child. Sadhana was named after her father's favorite actress-dancer [[Sadhana Bose]]. Her father was the elder brother of actor [[Hari Shivdasani]], father of actress [[Babita]].\n\nThe family migrated from [[Karachi]] during the post-[[Partition of India|Partition]] riots and settled in [[Mumbai]]. Her mother home-schooled her until she was 8 years old, after which she studied at Auxilium Convent, Wadala and [[Jai Hind College]]. Although they encountered difficult times, Sadhana was allowed to watch as many as two films. Sadhana was inspired to become a [[film actress]] and actress [[Nutan]] was said to have been her inspiration.<ref name=Interview1990>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=1d0vDKTadIBf_bIVfEbUgtk1MZsZnQ2THX2_AHnObVoM|title= Interview in Movie Magazine|author=Chandrika Bhattacharya |accessdate=3 February 2012|publisher=Movie Magazine|year=1990}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nSadhana aspired to be an actress since childhood. Her father helped her enter films. In 1955 she played a chorus girl in the song \"Mur mur ke na dekh mur mur ke\" in [[Raj Kapoor]]'s ''[[Shree 420]]''.<ref name=\"Song\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/feb/11dinesh.htm|title=Sadhana's Song|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=2 February 2012|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]}}</ref><ref name=Upperstall>{{cite web|url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/sadhana |title=Sadhana|publisher=Upperstall|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> When she was 15 years old, she was approached by some producers who had seen her act in a college play. They cast her in India's first Sindhi film titled ''Abaana'' (1958), where she played the role of [[Sheila Ramani]]'s younger sister.<ref name=Song/>\n\nA photograph of her publicizing ''Shree 420'' appeared in the movie magazine ''[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]''. It was then that [[Sashadhar Mukherjee]], one of Hindi cinema's leading producers at that time, noticed her. She joined Mukherjee's acting school along with her debutant co-star [[Joy Mukherjee]]. Sashadhar's son R.K. Nayyar, who had previously worked as assistant director on a few films, directed this film. He also created her trademark look, called the ''Sadhana cut'', inspired by British actress [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref name=Song/><ref name=Iconic>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/that-iconic-touch/757393/0|title=That Iconic Touch|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|accessdate=2 February 2012|author=Rajiv Vijayakar|location= Mumbai|date=4 March 2011}}</ref> The Filmalaya Production banner thus introduced Joy, Sadhana and her iconic hairstyle in their 1960 romantic film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. The film was declared a hit at the box office and was listed in the top 10 films of 1960.<ref name=Boxoffice1960>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=166&catName=MTk2MA==|title=Box Office 1960|website=Boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=3 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014060830/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=166&catName=MTk2MA==|archivedate=14 October 2013}}</ref> During this period she would again work under the same banner opposite Joy in ''[[Ek Musafir Ek Haseena]]''.<ref name=\"Love\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/mar/08dinesh.htm|title=Love in Simla: Grin fairytale|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=6 February 2012|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]}}</ref>\n\n===Stardom===\nBesides ''[[Love in Simla]]'', Sadhana was signed by acclaimed director [[Bimal Roy]] for his satirical film on Indian democracy, ''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]''. She portrayed a simple village girl in this multi-award-winning film. The film was a semi hit at box office and is known for the song \"O Sajna Barkha Bahar Aai\" sung by Lata Mangeshkar.\n\n====Major breakthrough====\n* 1961: ''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'' - In this 1961's hit film,<ref name=Boxoffice1961>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=167&catName=MTk2MQ==|title=Box Office 1961|website=Boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> ''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'', she played the love interest of [[Dev Anand]]. This black-and-white film was [[Film colourization|colourized]] and re-released in 2011. ''[[Rediff.com]]'' in the film's review writes about Sadhana: \"Her eyes, expressive and captivating, do most of the work, while she balances out her submissiveness with a firm tongue.\"<ref name=HumDono>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/hum-dono-review/20110204.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Hum Dono review: absolute must-watch|date=4 February 2011|author=Raja Sen|location=Mumbai|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> The duet \"Abhi na jaao chhodkar\" from the film ''Hum Dono'' is regarded as \"the most romantic song\" by actor [[Shah Rukh Khan]]<ref>{{cite news|title='Abhi na jao chhod kar...\u2019|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/-abhi-na-jao-chhod-kar/175554.html|newspaper=The Tribune|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> and director [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/veteran-actor-sadhana-takes-her-last-breath/article8028929.ece|title=Sadhana, Hindi film style icon of 1960s, is no more|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Author [[Amit Chaudhuri]] in an essay comparing cultures, says that Sadhana's curious expressions in the song denote listener's peculiar ecstasy while in other cinemas it would mean sex or love.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bh9iAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT196|title=Telling Tales: Selected Writing, 1993-2013|publisher=Penguin UK|author=Chaudhuri, Amit|authorlink=Amit Chaudhuri|year=2014|location=UK|isbn=9789351185963}}</ref>\n* 1962: ''Asli-Naqli'' - In 1962, she was again paired with [[Dev Anand]] in ''[[Asli-Naqli]]'' by director [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]]. The film has two hit songs \"Tujhe Jeevan Ki Dor Se\", sung by both [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and \"Tera Mera Pyar Amar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar. The same year saw director-screenwriter [[Raj Khosla]] cast her opposite Joy Mukherjee in ''[[Ek Musafir Ek Hasina]]''. She had debuted with Joy Mukherjee with the film ''Love in Shimla'' in 1960. Khosla would again work with Sadhana to make a suspense thriller trilogy.<ref name=\"ndtvbio\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/sadhana-shivdasani-bollywoods-mystery-girl-and-hasina-1258999|title=Sadhana Shivdasani, Bollywood's Mystery Girl and Hasina|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n* 1963: ''Mere Mehboob'' - This film was the highest grossing Indian film of 1963. The film stars Sadhana, [[Rajendra Kumar]], [[Ashok Kumar]], [[Nimmi]], Pran, [[Johnny Walker (actor)|Johnny Walker]] and [[Ameeta]]. In this film, Sadhana played her first role in the [[technicolour]] film. The film ''[[Mere Mehboob]]'' was directed by [[H. S. Rawail]]. The song \"Mere Mehboob Tujhe\" was shot in the University Hall and in a couple of places, one gets to see the University. The song became very popular upon release. The opening scene of the film shows the famous residential hall and the associated hall \"Victoria Gate\". The film was the blockbuster of 1963, and ranked in the top 5 films of the 1960s.\n* 1964: ''Woh Kaun Thi'' - In 1964, she played a double role in the first of the suspense-thriller trilogy; ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]''. This white-sari-clad performance opposite [[Manoj Kumar]] earned her first [[Filmfare]] nomination as Best Actress. Through this role she got to be part of [[Lata Mangeshkar]] \u2013 [[Madan Mohan]]\u2019s songs \"Naina barse\" and \"[[Lag jaa gale]]\". ''Rediff.com'' called her a show-stopper \"with an intriguing [[Mona Lisa]]-like smile\". The film was a box office hit. Raj Khosla cast her in two more successful mystery films; ''[[Mera Saaya]]'' (1966) and ''[[Anita (1967 film)|Anita]]'' (1967) thus making her famous as the \"Mystery girl\".\n*1965 : Arzoo- Arzoo was a box office success, with Sadhana, Rajendra Kumar and Feroz Khan in lead roles. The film had songs like \"Ae Phoolon ki Rani\" sung by Mohammad Rafi and \" Aji rooth kar ab\" , sung by Lata Mangeshkar.\n* 1966: ''Mera Saaya'' - ''Mera Saaya'' was a box office success, a courtroom drama film, again saw her playing a double role, now opposite [[Sunil Dutt]]. The film was the third film directed by Raj Khosla with Sadhana. The song \"Jhumka gira re\" sung by [[Asha Bhosle]] and composed by [[Madan Mohan]] saw Sadhana perform dance steps choreographed by [[Saroj Khan]]. Khan was then an assistant to dance director [[B. Sohanlal]]. The song became so popular that excited audience in cinema halls used to throw coins at the screen, and is one of the most requested songs on the radio. The film also had the classic songs \"Mera Saaya Saath Hoga\" and \"Nainon Mein Badra Chhaye\", both voiced by [[Lata Mangeshkar]].\n* 1965: ''Waqt''- In this 1965 drama film, Sadhana appeared alongside Sunil Dutt. For her performance in this hit film, Sadhana got her second Filmfare nomination as Best Actress for the role of Meena, in Yash Chopra's directorial saga ''Waqt'' (1965). She stood out in Bollywood's first ever ensemble cast by bringing out the fashion of tight ''churidar-kurtas''. The song has hit Hindi songs such as \"Aye Meri Zohra Zabeen\", sung by Manna Dey, \"Hum Jab Simat Ke\", sung by Mahendra Kapoor and Asha Bhosle, \"Waqt Se Din Aur Raat\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and \"Aage Bhi Jaane Na Tu\", sung by Asha Bhosle. The film proved to be 1965's \"blockbuster hit\".\n* 1967: ''Anita'' - In this 1967 suspense film, Sadhana appeared alongside Manoj Kumar with whom she had starred in lead role in the blockbuster film ''Woh Kaun Thi''. This was the last film of the suspense-thriller trilogy of Khosla-Sadhana partnership.\n*1969: ''Inteqam'' - This film was directed by R.K. Nayyar, and stars Sadhana and Sanjay Khan in lead roles and supported by Ashok Kumar, Jeevan, Rajendra Nath, Rehman, Helen and Anju Mahendru. The film features the first cabaret number song \"Aa Jaane Jaan\", also a rarity through her career. The film was a success at box office and marked the return of Sadhana after her brief illness, and her husband directed the film.\n\nHer other notable works in the 1960s include performances in [[Gaban (1966 film)|''Gaban'']] (1966) and ''[[Budtameez]]'' (1966). Sadhana and Shammi Kapoor worked together in 4 films Rajkumar, Budtameez, Sachaai and Chhote Sarkar of which the first 3 were box office hits and the pair got good audience acceptance''.''\n\n* 1964: ''Rajkumar'' - ''Rajkumar'' stars Sadhana, [[Shammi Kapoor]], Pran, [[Prithviraj Kapoor]], [[Om Prakash]] and [[Rajindernath]]. The film was a box office success and has the hit songs \"Aaja Aai Bahar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar, \"Tumne Pukara Aur Hum Chale Aaye\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and [[Suman Kalyanpur]], \"Tumne Kisi Ki Jaan Ko\" and \"Is Rang Badalti Duniya Mein\", both sung by Mohammed Rafi. \n*1969: Sachaai - Sachaai stars Sadhana, Shammi Kapoor , Sanjeev Kumar, Helen, Johnny Walker and Pran. This film was a box office hit with songs like \" Sau baras ki zindagi\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and Asha Bhosle \" Ae dost mere maine duniya dekhi hai\" , sung by Mohammed Rafi and Manna Dey and \" Mere gunaah maaf kar\" sung by Mohammed Rafi.\n* 1969: ''Ek Phool Do Mali'' - This Indian Hindi film of 1969 stars Sadhana and Sanjay Khan in lead roles and has hit songs such as \"Ye Parda Hata Do\", sung by Asha Bhosle and Mohammed Rafi, \"Aulad Walo\", sung by Asha Bhosle and Mohammed Rafi, \"O Nanhe Se Farishte\" sung by Mohammed Rafi, \"Saiyan Le Gayi Jiya\", sung by Asha Bhosle and \"Tujhe Suraj Kahoon Ya Chanda\" sung by [[Manna Dey]].\n\n===End of acting career===\n[[File:Nanda-Waheeda-Helen-Sadhana.jpg|thumb|right|Sadhana (first from right) with [[Helen (actress)|Helen]], [[Waheeda Rehman]] and [[Nanda (actress)|Nanda]] in 2010]]\nSadhana had health issues due to her thyroid, which she got treated in [[Boston]]. After returning from the US, she starred in the successful movies Intaquam (1969), Ek phool do mali (1969), Sachaai (1969), Dil Daulat Duniya (1972) and Geeta Mera Naam (1974).\n\nIn ''[[Intaquam]]'' she played the role of a woman who revengefully lures the son of her own boss who cheated her, to be put behind the bars for a crime he did not commit. In 1974, her directorial venture ''[[Geeta Mera Naam]]'' was released. Produced by her husband, the film had herself playing the lead actress along with [[Sunil Dutt]] and [[Feroz Khan (actor, born 1939)|Feroz Khan]]. It was also [[Saroj Khan]]'s first film as an independent dance director..\n\nAfter that, she retired from acting, as she did not want to be cast as a side-actress or do character roles.<ref name=Song/> Later, she and her husband formed a production company. She also produced the movie ''Pati Parmeshwar'', starring [[Dimple Kapadia]] in 1989.<ref name=Hindu>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|author=Das Gupta, Ranjan|title=Sadhna worked wonders|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2008/09/05/stories/2008090550840400.htm|date=5 September 2008|accessdate=3 February 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSadhana married her ''Love in Simla'' director Ram Krishna Nayyar on 7 March 1966.<ref name=\"MeraSaaya\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jun/20dinesh.htm|title=Mera Saaya: A Compelling Conundrum|last=|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> Their love blossomed on the film set. But as she was very young then, her parents opposed it. They were married for nearly thirty years, until his death in 1995 from asthma. The couple had no children. In 2013, she stated that doesn't keep in touch with her cousin [[Babita]] but does keep in touch with actresses such as [[Asha Parekh]], [[Waheeda Rehman]], [[Nanda (actress)|Nanda]] and [[Helen Jairag Richardson]].<ref>http://timesofIndia.Indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-dont-acknowledge-Babita-Sadhana/articleshow/26720515.cms</ref>\n\nShe suffered from eye problems due to [[hyperthyroidism]]. After her retirement from acting, she refused to be photographed.<ref name=Iconic/> Living in [[Santacruz, Mumbai]], she rented an apartment building owned by singer [[Asha Bhosle]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-08-13/news-interviews/28298083_1_sangeeta-bungalow-sadhana-yusuf-lakdawala|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|title=Builder threatened to kill me: Sadhana|date=13 August 2012|author=Deeptiman Tiwary|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-dont-acknowledge-Babita-Sadhana/articleshow/26720515.cms|title=I don't acknowledge Babita: Sadhana|work=The Times of India|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Fashion icon==\nSadhana introduced the [[Bangs (hair)|fringe]] hairstyle in the Indian film industry in her first film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. R.K. Nayyar, director of the film and her future husband, suggested the fringe style in order to make her forehead look narrower. Sadhana says: \"They tried to stick a strip near the hair-line, but it didn\u2019t work out.\"<ref name=Interview1990/> Nayyar then suggested she go for the fringe style as was then sported by the Hollywood actress [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref name=Song/><ref name=Iconic/><ref name=Hindu/> The fringe soon became popular and a fashion fad in the 1960s.<ref name=HT>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Fashion/Sadhana-s-fringe-benefits-from-Audrey-Hepburn/Article1-738866.aspx|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|title=Sadhana's fringe benefits from Audrey Hepburn|location=Mumbai|date=28 August 2011|author=Roshmila Bhattacharya|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Fashion>{{cite book|title=Fashion cultures: Theories, explorations, and analysis|author1=[[Stella Bruzzi]] |author2=Pamela Church Gibson |year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-20685-5|page=188|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xmjv-IJymZsC&pg=PA188 }}</ref>\n\nThe style was copied by girls in India and is still known by the same name.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Rachel Dwyer |author2=Divia Patel |title=Cinema India: the visual culture of Hindi film |publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2002|page=97|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebsaAQAAIAAJ&q=sadhana+cut&dq=sadhana+cut }}</ref> The look suited the role of naughty, pretty, glamorous Sonia that she played. But when Sadhana went on the shoot for [[Bimal Roy]]'s ''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]'', Roy was disappointed to see her modern look. She had to stick her fringe back in order to match the simple village girl she played here.<ref name=Interview1990/> In 1963, when she signed to play a role of a simple Muslim girl from Aligarh in ''[[Mere Mehboob]]'', Sadhana undid her famous \"Sadhana cut\" to fit the bill. She had centre-parted her hair and wore it in a plait, which was immediately discarded by the director H.S. Rawail. He said that the audience wanted to see her signature \"Sadhana cut\" and demanded it.<ref name=Interview1991/> Recently, the Bollywood actress [[Deepika Padukone]] sported the same fringe in her films ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' (2007) and ''[[Chandni Chowk To China]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110404/jsp/entertainment/story_13805378.jsp|title=Mirror Mirror|newspaper=The Telegraph India|date=4 April 2011|author=Priscilla Corner|accessdate=5 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSadhana is also credited with bringing into fashion the tight ''churidar-kurta''.<ref name=Interview1991/><ref name=Fashion/> She went with this concept of gracefully changing the traditional loose [[salwar kameez]] to her director [[Yash Chopra]] for the 1965 film ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]]''. Chopra felt insecure and thought that it would not be accepted. But Sadhana, with the help of her fashion designer [[Bhanu Athaiya]] showed him a sample, which he liked.<ref name=Interview1990/> The trend lasted well into the 1970s and can be seen, adopted by many actresses.<ref name=Encyclo>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|author=[[Gulzar]], [[Govind Nihalani]], Saibal Chatterjee|publisher=Popular Prakashan|page=523|isbn=81-7991-066-0|year=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT547 }}</ref>\n\nIn a song sequence of \"[[Phir Milenge Chalte Chalte]]\" for ''[[Rab Ne Bana Di Jodi]]'' (2008), actress [[Bipasha Basu]] dressed herself in a white ''churidar-kurta'' and also frolicked with the famous fringe as a tribute to Sadhana.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/DressCircle/I-m-not-going-to-risk-my-life-for-any-film/Article1-367020.aspx|title=I'm not going to risk my life for any film|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=15 January 2009|author=Subhash K. Jha|location=Mumbai|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sadhana made a rare public appearance walking the ramp in a pink sari at a fashion show to support the cause for cancer and AIDS patients. She was escorted by her relative, actor [[Ranbir Kapoor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/veteran-actress-sadhana-walks-the-ramp-with-ranbir-kapoor/#sadhana-ranbir-gs|title=Veteran actress Sadhana walks the ramp with Ranbir Kapoor|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=11 May 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nDespite the fact that many of Shivdasani's films fared very well at the [[box office]], she did not receive any of the leading awards of the film industry. She was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award]] in [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress category]] for her roles in ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' and ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]].\n\nFor her contribution to film, she was awarded the [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]] by the [[International Indian Film Academy Awards|IIFA]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iifa.com/web07/showcase/2002-winnerslist.htm|title=Showcase: IIFA 2002 Malaysia|publisher=IIFA|accessdate=14 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329033936/http://www.iifa.com/web07/showcase/2002-winnerslist.htm|archivedate=29 March 2007|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000361/2002|publisher=IMDB|title=Awards of the International Indian Film Academy (2002)|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDuring her later years, Sadhana was involved in court cases<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/3-court-cases-were-wearing-her-out-says-sadhanas-lawyer/|title=3 court cases were wearing her out, says Sadhana\u2019s lawyer|date=2015-12-26|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-02-12|language=en-US}}</ref> and suffered from illness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ailing Sadhana pleaded for help but no one from the film industry came forward: Tabassum|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/ailing-sadhana-pleaded-for-help-but-no-one-from-the-film-industry-came-forward-tabassum|last=Sahadevan|first=Sonup|work=The Indian Express|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> She had undergone an emergency surgery due to a bleeding oral lesion in December 2014 at the [[K J Somaiya Medical College]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Veteran actress Sadhana on the mend after emergency surgery|last=Pandit|first=Sadaguru|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/veteran-actress-sadhana-on-the-mend-after-emergency-surgery/15839157|work=Mid Day|date=13 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Yesteryear actress Sadhana undergoes a major surgery|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141212/entertainment-bollywood/article/yestyear-actress-sadhana-undergoes-major-surgery|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nSadhana died on 25 December 2015 in [[P.D. Hinduja National Hospital and Medical Research Centre|Hinduja Hospital]], Mumbai after being hospitalised with high fever.<ref name=hindu/> Although the illness she briefly suffered from was officially undisclosed,<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadhana, Hindi film style icon of 1960s, is no more|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/veteran-actor-sadhana-takes-her-last-breathe/article8028929.ece|work=The Hindu|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Sadhana was cremated at Oshiwara crematorium in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. Bollywood stars such [[Anushka Sharma]], [[Karan Johar]], [[Madhur Bhandarkar]], [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and several others expressed their sorrow at the loss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bollywood mourns veteran actor Sadhana\u2019s death|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/bollywood-mourns-veteran-actor-sadhana-s-death/story-OGkdVEKGvR91ZUhtICcizJ.html|work=Hindustan Times|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=RIP Sadhana: Lag Jaa Gale to Jhumka Gira Re, remembering the actor through her songs|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rip-sadhana-laj-jaa-gale-to-jhumka-gira-re-remembering-the-actor-through-her-songs/1/555187.html|last=Nijhara|first=Apoorva|work=India Today|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Movie !! Role !! Note \n|-\n| 1955 || '''''[[Shree 420]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Chorus girl || Cameo role in the song \"Mud Mud Ke Na Dekh\"\n|-\n| 1958 || '''''[[Abana (film)|Abana]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || || First [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] film \n|-\n| 1958  ||Sahara ||\n|-\n| 1960 || '''''[[Love in Simla]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Sonia || Sadhana debut film as a lead actress \n|-\n| 1960 || '''''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Seema ||Hit Song \"O Sajna Barkha Bahar\" \n|-\n| 1961 || '''''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Mita ||Hit Song \"Abhi Na Jao Chodkar\", a duet by [[Asha Bhosle]] and [[Mohammed Rafi]] \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Prem Patra]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Kavita Kapoor ||\n|-\n| 1962 || '''''Man Mauji'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\">{{cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/519618/part-several-evergreen-films-sadhana.html | title=Part of several evergreen films, Sadhana no more | work=[[Deccan Herald]] | date=26 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> || Rani || \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Ek Musafir Ek Hasina]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Asha || \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Asli-Naqli]]'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Renu ||Hit songs from the film are \"Tere Mera Pyar Amar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar, and \"Tujhe Jeevan Ki Durse\", a duet by Lata Mangeshkar and Mohammed Rafi \n|-\n| 1963 || '''''[[Mere Mehboob]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Husna Banu Changezi || Hit Song \"Mere Mehboob Tujhe Mer